			<td class="BoardRowA"><a name="7159475"><span style="font-weight: bold;">
				Future AC players, you might like this :)
			</span></a></td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				I have been playing AC for quite awhile and made a L94 mage on the Morningthaw server before I sold him on eBay (Yes, you CAN use eBay). Prior to the sale of my account, I offered twinking services, which again I used eBay to lure business. I have sold my account and started over at step 1. I'm not trolling for business :) Hard to twink people when you don't play. <br>  <br> Now, since no one likes being a newbie again, here's a couple good templates you may want to start with. My email address is halleck@mindspring.com if you have any questions, or you may visit  <a class=BoardRowBLink target="_blank" href="http://www.baalzevuv.com/aluvian">http://www.baalzevuv.com/aluvian</a>  and post on the forum there. Btw, I am loathe to censorship, thus my desire to stick it to Verant ;)  <br>  <br> Mage Templates:  <br>  <br> No matter what you hear, Og Templates are horrible. Og translates to : Waste of 8 useful skill credits. Og's only purpose is being semi-useful if you're under level 40. After level 40, you'll be kickin' yourself for not having all the skills you really like.  <br>  <br> There are three types of mage templates I would use.  <br>  <br> ***********  <br> Template 1: &quot;Pure-Mage&quot;  <br>  <br> If you're an avid player killer, you're going to want to invest some time in a relatively difficult template that doesn't begin to unfold until L50 (attainable within a month at 4+ hours a day of power levelling). Not only is it a fine player killer template, it's great for solo or questing. A lot of this will seem Greek until you get into game.  <br>  <br> RACE: Gharu'ndin (Atlan Staff = KING)  <br> ATTRIBUTES:  <br> 50/60/10/10/100/100  <br>  <br> SPECIALIZED:  <br> Life Magic (Almost necessary)  <br> Magic Defense (Necessary for serious PK)  <br> Loyalty (Two extra skill credits. May as well)  <br>  <br> TRAINED:  <br> War Magic  <br>  <br> At level 6, train Mana Conversion. At level 20, train Creature Magic (In my opinion, this is more valuable than item magic for levelling . Portal travel with Item Magic is convenient, but not necessary). At level 50, train Item magic.  <br>  <br> ***********  <br> Template 2: &quot;Uber-Imperil Tank Bitch.&quot;  <br>  <br> If you intend on playing with a room mate or friend only, you may want to consider this template for nominal levelling gains (if your partner is of a warrior class). In the long run, this template is nothing but joy if you're hunting in large groups. I have one of these at L37, and have been casting L6 spells in the three magic classes since level L34.  <br>  <br> RACE: Doesn't matter.  <br> ATTRIBUTES:  <br> 25/85/10/10/100/100  <br>  <br> SPECIALIZED:  <br> Life Magic (Necessary for Imperil)  <br> Magic Defense (Necessary for tanking)  <br> Mana Conversion (Useful)  <br>  <br> TRAINED:  <br> Healing (Useful for tanking)  <br>  <br> At level 9, train Creature Magic. At level 26, train Item Magic. Afterwards, train whatever. I suggest Arcane Lore, Leadership or Lockpick.  <br>  <br> ***********  <br> Template 3: &quot;Do all&quot;  <br>  <br> This is a template similar to Baalzevuv. It is modified for better PK combat and unusual situations where your dagger is necessary (Chorazite quests).  <br>  <br> RACE: Aluvian  <br> ATTRIBUTES:  <br> 25/30/65/10/100/100  <br>  <br> SPECIALIZED:  <br> Arcane Lore (2 extra skill credits)  <br>  <br> TRAINED:  <br> Life Magic  <br> Mana Conversion  <br> Melee Defense  <br> War Magic  <br>  <br> At level 9 train Creature Magic. At level 26, train Item Magic. From there, it doesn't really matter. I suggest Healing first then leadership or lockpick.  <br> **************************  <br>  <br> Melee Class Templates:  <br>  <br> If you're creating a melee or bow class character, keep in mind that magic IS necessary to be successful. This is one of the largest differences between EQ and AC, the ability to blend classes. Since there are countless ways to make a melee class, I'll give a few pointers of what you want, and what you DON'T want.  <br>  <br> Item magic IS needed. Don't specialize it, though. It should ALWAYS be trained. You also want to start with 100 strength unless you're making a dagger fighter or archer (Start with 100 coordination). It is not necessary to specialize melee defense. In my opinion, it's a waste of skill credits since the important part of your melee defense comes from casting Defender on your weapon. Avoid having multiple melee skills. In my opinion, axe is the the best melee skill. Also, healing is a necessary skill for all melee/bow classes.  <br>  <br> An ideal template for an axe user would be:  <br>  <br> RACE: Aluvian or Sho: Race weapon has piercing damage. Axe doesn't.  <br> ATTRIBUTES:  <br> 100/30/50/50/70/30  <br>  <br> SPECIALIZED:  <br> Axe  <br>  <br> TRAINED:  <br> Creature Magic  <br> Healing  <br> Item Magic  <br> Mana Conversion  <br> Melee Defense  <br>  <br> At level 5, train Arcane Lore (Melee fighters are somewhat dependent on this skill). At level 26, train life magic. After that, it really doesn't matter. Keep in mind, this template is intended for characters that hit L50+. If you want a quick bang for your buck, start with less focus/self and add it to your coordination or quickness. You won't be that adept with magic, and that's the big issue higher up in levels.  <br>  <br> There are templates termed as &quot;Extreme Templates.&quot; These the most difficult, but most powerful melee characters you can make (At L60+). My favorite Extreme Template is the bastardized Dagger/Mage/Archer.  <br>  <br> RACE: ALUVIAN (Dagger)  <br> ATTRIBUTES:  <br> 10,10,100,10,100,100  <br>  <br> SPECIALIZED:  <br> Dagger  <br> Healing  <br>  <br> TRAINED:  <br> Creature Magic  <br> Life Magic  <br> Mana Conversion  <br> Melee Defense  <br>  <br> At level 9, train Item magic. At level 26, train bow. At level 40, train Arcane Lore. Make note that you need someone to twink your character since they're horribly difficult to play up til L35. You'll find the Amulet of Lifegiver is your friend.  <br>  <br> **********  <br> Every monster you kill gives you a bit of experience you may invest into your skill. To optimize how you spend your experience, follow a few simple rules of budget spending.  <br>  <br> Attributes only exist to compliment your skills. The formula for determining your base Healing skill is (Coordination + Focus)/3. With that in mind, you know that Coordination and Focus should be equal in cost and the experience needed to raise a point of healing should cost three times as much as one point of focus. Now, it's tricky to do the math for multiple skills, but if you focus on one skill at a time, always follow this rule of thumb.  <br>  <br> Also remember the damage modifiers. Each melee/bow class uses strength or coordination to determine the minimum damage done to a monster. If you're a sword user, the last thing you want to do is start with anything less than 100 strength.  <br>  <br> Anyways, I hope this little guide will answer some of your questions. Excuse poor grammar or spelling errors. I'm not going to bother proofreading. Good luck in Asheron's Call!  <br>  <br> Halleck  <br> (Formerly known as Baalzevuv, L94 badass tyrant philanthropist of Morningthaw) 		

